<img src="http://pages.cthome.net/filanwizard/filansig3.jpg"></a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uburrowowlx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>burrowowlx</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(10/3/01 4:13:46 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Melee dmg v caster dmg.</span><hr size=1> If wizards did more long term damage than rogues, there would be no reason for rogues.  I agree.  Perhaps the same goes with monks.  I do not object to these two classes doing more damage long term than wizards.<br>
<br>
I object to these two classes doing 5 times the long term damage over wizards.<br>
<br>
Yes, being able to crank up the damage you do in a hurry is valuable.  But it's not valuable enough to make up for the huge gap between melee and caster damage.<br>
<br>
I object to warriors doing more damage, both long term and short term, than wizards.  They have tons more defensive abilities, it is not fair to also give them tons of offensive abilities.<br>
<br>
And ultimately, we are arguing a useless arguement.  The single pull mez group is the absolute worst way to get XP, and I would refuse to join them even when invited.  Quad kiting and AoE groups are vastly superior.<br>
<br>
But that doesn't mean I want to suck in single pull groups compared to rogues, dammit   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grimicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(10/3/01 9:46:10 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grim3.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Melee dmg v caster dmg.</span><hr size=1> You feel bad, imagine being a post 50 level Monk who can, every NINE minutes, attempt a supercharged flying kick that does about the same as a once-per-10-second backstab by a level 30 Rogue. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uhiraghm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hiraghm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(10/3/01 10:02:05 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/jdwilliams2/data/Aldrinshroom1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Melee dmg v caster dmg.</span><hr size=1> It doesn't bother me if the wizard does the most damage or not, or even as much. It used to, but I grew out of it. What I really want is entertainment. Root n Nuke gets boring. blast blast, med med gets boring. Nifty spells and toys are entertaining. One of harvest's biggest bonuses is, to me, the spell effect.<br>
<br>
A mage summons; he summons tank-wizard pets, he summons the direct damage he does, he summons toys.<br>
An enchanter screws with your mind. Illusions, charms, *magic-based* damage, etcs.<br>
<br>
What is a wizard? <br>
A wizard seems to have the following specialties:<br>
telekinetics (transporting things/people)<br>
Area Effect (spells that cover an area or group)<br>
*Thermal control*...<br>
<br>
Ever notice that all wizard damage is based on heat or cold? Maybe that's why it's so mana efficient. How about giving wizards heat/cold based resists that are superior to everyone else's? And use less mana? We have the staff of temperate flux that debuffs a little fire resist.. what debuffs cold resist? I'm only 48... but do we get a cold-based dmg shield, ever?<br>
<br>
How's this for a spell series that uses our design:<br>
Trap of Solusek: an AE spell (maybe indoor only) you cast it, and that area becomes a trap; the next mob that passes through it triggers it, takes X dmg, disperses the trap. It might be okay to have it last a set period if time with all mobs taking dmg, but that's too much like an AE dot.<br>
Of course there would be the cold-based equivalent. If they're indoor only, maybe rangers/druids could have trap of thorns for outdoors (which would last a period of time and be a dot.)<br>
Deflection: again, an area trap.. mob passes through it and is randomly relocated...<br>
Wormhole: yet another area trap, trickier to implement. Wizard would control entrance/exit somehow. Mob go in here, mob come out there. Dispersing the wormhole in the process of course. I can see where this one could be severely abused.<br>
The deflection trap could be real handy during a retreat.<br>
Temporal Anomaly: mob is knocked back along its course 5 seconds. In other words, where it was 5 seconds ago, there it is now. Or 10 seconds, or 3 ticks. Whatever works out. probably 2X casting time. There obviously would have to be a long recast delay.<br>
Barrier of cold/Barrier of heat: Sort-of a divine aura type spell: a wall of ice/fire appears a few feet in front of the wizard. Doesn't do damage. Can't dmg the mobs through it, lasts maybe 10 or 20 seconds, takes a component. But the mobs can't harm you through it either. They *can* go around it, and they will eventually beat it down. maybe have dmg the wall takes determine how long it lasts. Or have the cold wall be higher level than fire wall, be beat-downable, but have fire wall do dmg and not be beat-downable (but last a shorter time.)<br>
<br>
These are spells which, imo, would make wizards more cool.<br>
And I'd rather be cool than damage dealing.<br>
<br>
Aldrin Moonwalker<br>
